ccre.log

Class LogLevel

  • java.lang.Object
    • ccre.log.LogLevel

  • public class LogLevel
extends java.lang.Object
    Represents a Logging level. This represents how important/severe a logging message is. The levels are, in order of descending severity: severe, warning, info, config, fine, finer, finest.

    • Field Detail

      • SEVERE

        public static final LogLevel SEVERE
        A severe error. This usually means that something major didn't work, or an impossible condition occurred.

      • WARNING

        public static final LogLevel WARNING
        A warning. This usually means that something bad happened, but most things should probably still work.

      • INFO

        public static final LogLevel INFO
        A piece of info. This usually means something happened that the user might want to know.

      • CONFIG

        public static final LogLevel CONFIG
        A piece of configuration information. This usually means something that isn't really important, but is something triggered by configuration instead of normal operation.

      • FINE

        public static final LogLevel FINE
        A top-level debugging message. This can be caused by anything, but probably shouldn't be logged particularly often.

      • FINER

        public static final LogLevel FINER
        A mid-level debugging message. This can be caused by anything, and can be logged relatively often.

      • FINEST

        public static final LogLevel FINEST
        A low-level debugging message. This can be caused by anything, and might be called many times per second.

      • id

        public final byte id
        The ID of the LogLevel. The higher, the more severe. SEVERE is 9, FINEST is -9, for example.

      • message

        public final java.lang.String message
        The long-form message representing this level.
